description:
FOUR PILLARS OF OOP:

1. ENCAPSULATION
   Private fields + public getters/setters
   class Account {
     private double balance;
     public double getBalance() { return balance; }
     public void deposit(double amount) {
       if (amount > 0) balance += amount;
     }
   }

2. INHERITANCE
   class Animal { void speak() { } }
   class Dog extends Animal {
     @Override void speak() { System.out.println("Woof"); }
   }
   • Java supports single inheritance (one parent class)
   • Multiple inheritance via interfaces

3. POLYMORPHISM
   Animal a = new Dog();  // runtime polymorphism
   a.speak();             // calls Dog.speak() — dynamic dispatch
   // Compile-time: method overloading (same name, different params)

4. ABSTRACTION
   • Abstract class: cannot be instantiated, may have abstract methods
   • Interface: contract — all methods implicitly public abstract (pre-Java 8)

KEY KEYWORDS:
  this  — reference to current object instance
  super — reference to parent class; super() calls parent constructor
  static — belongs to class, not instance
  final — variable: constant; method: cannot override; class: cannot extend

CLASS MEMBERS:
  class Person {
    private String name;          // field
    public Person(String name) {  // constructor
      this.name = name;
    }
    public String getName() { return name; }  // method
    static int count = 0;         // static field
  }

INTERFACE vs ABSTRACT CLASS:
  Interface: no state (fields must be static final), multiple inheritance
  Abstract class: can have state, constructors, concrete methods
  Java 8+: interfaces can have default and static methods

EXCEPTION HIERARCHY:
  Throwable
  ├── Error (JVM errors — don't catch: OutOfMemoryError, StackOverflowError)
  └── Exception
      ├── Checked (must handle: IOException, SQLException)
      └── RuntimeException (Unchecked: NullPointerException, ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException)

SYNTAX:
  try {
    // risky code
    int result = 10 / divisor;
  } catch (ArithmeticException e) {
    System.out.println("Division by zero: " + e.getMessage());
  } catch (Exception e) {
    e.printStackTrace();  // log the full stack trace
  } finally {
    // always runs — use for resource cleanup
    connection.close();
  }

TRY-WITH-RESOURCES (Java 7+):
  try (FileReader fr = new FileReader("file.txt")) {
    // fr is automatically closed after block
  }  // implements AutoCloseable

throws vs throw:
  // throws: declares checked exceptions method can propagate
  public void readFile(String path) throws IOException { }
  // throw: actually throws an exception
  throw new IllegalArgumentException("Name cannot be null");

CUSTOM EXCEPTIONS:
  class InsufficientFundsException extends RuntimeException {
    private final double amount;
    public InsufficientFundsException(double amount) {
      super("Insufficient funds. Needed: " + amount);
      this.amount = amount;
    }
    public double getAmount() { return amount; }
  }
  // Usage:
  throw new InsufficientFundsException(500.0);

SPRING BOOT EXCEPTION HANDLING:
  @RestControllerAdvice
  public class GlobalExceptionHandler {
    @ExceptionHandler(InsufficientFundsException.class)
    public ResponseEntity<ErrorResponse> handle(InsufficientFundsException e) {
      return ResponseEntity.badRequest().body(new ErrorResponse(e.getMessage()));
    }
  }

COLLECTIONS HIERARCHY:
  Collection
  ├── List — ordered, allows duplicates
  │   ├── ArrayList  — dynamic array, O(1) get, O(n) insert middle
  │   ├── LinkedList — doubly linked, O(1) insert/delete, O(n) get
  │   └── Vector     — synchronized ArrayList (legacy)
  ├── Set — no duplicates
  │   ├── HashSet    — O(1) ops, unordered
  │   ├── LinkedHashSet — preserves insertion order
  │   └── TreeSet    — sorted, O(log n) ops
  └── Queue
      ├── LinkedList  — also Queue/Deque
      ├── PriorityQueue — min-heap by default
      └── ArrayDeque  — fast stack/queue operations

  Map (not Collection)
  ├── HashMap      — O(1) avg, unordered, allows null key
  ├── LinkedHashMap — preserves insertion order
  ├── TreeMap      — sorted by key, O(log n)
  └── Hashtable    — synchronized, legacy (use ConcurrentHashMap instead)

COMPARABLE vs COMPARATOR:
  // Comparable — natural ordering (in the class itself)
  class Employee implements Comparable<Employee> {
    public int compareTo(Employee o) {
      return this.salary - o.salary;  // ascending by salary
    }
  }
  Collections.sort(list);  // uses compareTo

  // Comparator — external / custom ordering
  Comparator<Employee> byName = (a, b) -> a.name.compareTo(b.name);
  list.sort(byName);
  // Or: Comparator.comparing(Employee::getName).reversed()

GENERICS:
  List<String> names = new ArrayList<>();   // type-safe
  Map<String, Integer> freq = new HashMap<>();
  public <T> T findFirst(List<T> list) { return list.get(0); }
  // Bounded: <T extends Number> — T must be Number or subclass

FILE HANDLING:
  // Read all lines
  List<String> lines = Files.readAllLines(Path.of("file.txt"));
  // Write
  Files.writeString(Path.of("out.txt"), content);
  // Stream lines (large files)
  Files.lines(path).forEach(System.out::println);

MEMORY & GC:
  Heap: new objects go here; GC reclaims unreachable objects
  Stack: method calls and local primitives
  GC types: Serial, Parallel, G1 (default Java 9+), ZGC (low-latency)
  Prevent leaks: close streams, remove listeners, avoid static collections

LAMBDA EXPRESSIONS:
A concise way to write anonymous functions.

  // Before Java 8
  Runnable r = new Runnable() {
    public void run() { System.out.println("Hello"); }
  };

  // Java 8 lambda
  Runnable r = () -> System.out.println("Hello");

SYNTAX:
  (params) -> expression
  (params) -> { statements; return value; }
  param -> expression  // single param, no parens

FUNCTIONAL INTERFACES (java.util.function):
  @FunctionalInterface = interface with exactly ONE abstract method

  Function<T,R>     — takes T, returns R   — apply()
  Consumer<T>       — takes T, returns void — accept()
  Supplier<T>       — takes nothing, returns T — get()
  Predicate<T>      — takes T, returns boolean — test()
  BiFunction<T,U,R> — takes T and U, returns R

EXAMPLES:
  Function<String, Integer> len = s -> s.length();
  len.apply("hello");  // 5

  Predicate<Integer> isEven = n -> n % 2 == 0;
  isEven.test(4);  // true

  Consumer<String> print = System.out::println;
  print.accept("hi");

  Supplier<List<String>> newList = ArrayList::new;

METHOD REFERENCES (shorthand for lambdas):
  // Static method
  Function<String, Integer> f = Integer::parseInt;
  // Instance method (object)
  Consumer<String> print = System.out::println;
  // Instance method (class)
  Function<String, String> upper = String::toUpperCase;
  // Constructor
  Supplier<ArrayList> create = ArrayList::new;

COMPOSING FUNCTIONS:
  Function<Integer, Integer> doubleIt = x -> x * 2;
  Function<Integer, Integer> addTen  = x -> x + 10;
  Function<Integer, Integer> both = doubleIt.andThen(addTen);  // double THEN add
  both.apply(5);  // (5*2)+10 = 20

OPTIONAL:
A container that may or may not hold a non-null value.
Eliminate NullPointerException from your codebase.

  Optional<String> name = Optional.of("Alice");      // must be non-null
  Optional<String> empty = Optional.empty();
  Optional<String> nullable = Optional.ofNullable(getValue()); // safe

  // Consuming safely
  name.isPresent()                     // true/false check
  name.get()                           // throws if empty — avoid!
  name.orElse("default")              // value or default
  name.orElseGet(() -> computeDefault()) // lazy default
  name.orElseThrow(NoSuchElementException::new)
  name.map(String::toUpperCase)        // transform if present
  name.filter(n -> n.length() > 3)     // filter
  name.ifPresent(System.out::println)  // consume if present

  // Chaining
  Optional<String> city = Optional.ofNullable(user)
    .map(User::getAddress)
    .map(Address::getCity);

DATE & TIME API (java.time — Java 8):
Replaces the broken java.util.Date and Calendar.

  LocalDate    — date only (2024-01-15)
  LocalTime    — time only (14:30:00)
  LocalDateTime — date + time (2024-01-15T14:30:00)
  ZonedDateTime — with timezone
  Instant      — machine timestamp (epoch milliseconds)
  Duration     — time-based amount (hours, minutes, seconds)
  Period       — date-based amount (years, months, days)

EXAMPLES:
  LocalDate today = LocalDate.now();
  LocalDate dob   = LocalDate.of(2000, 3, 15);
  Period age = Period.between(dob, today);
  System.out.println(age.getYears()); // years old

  LocalDateTime dt = LocalDateTime.now();
  dt.plusDays(7);         // immutable — returns new instance
  dt.format(DateTimeFormatter.ofPattern("dd/MM/yyyy HH:mm"));

  // Convert to legacy Date
  Date legacy = Date.from(Instant.now());

CALLABLE & FUTURE:
  Callable<String> task = () -> longRunningOp();
  ExecutorService exec = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(4);
  Future<String> future = exec.submit(task);
  String result = future.get();  // blocks until done

COMPLETABLE FUTURE:
  CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> fetchUser(id))
    .thenApply(user -> user.getName().toUpperCase())
    .thenAccept(System.out::println)
    .exceptionally(ex -> { log(ex); return null; });

  // Combine
  CompletableFuture.allOf(cf1, cf2, cf3).thenRun(() -> done());

VAR (Java 10) — local type inference:
  var list = new ArrayList<String>();  // inferred as ArrayList<String>
  var map  = new HashMap<String, Integer>();
  // Only for local variables — NOT fields or return types
  // Makes code shorter without losing type safety

SWITCH EXPRESSIONS (Java 14):
  // Old switch (statement)
  String result;
  switch (day) {
    case MON: result = "Weekday"; break;
    case SAT: result = "Weekend"; break;
    default:  result = "Other";
  }

  // New switch (expression) — no fall-through, returns value
  String result = switch (day) {
    case MON, TUE, WED, THU, FRI -> "Weekday";
    case SAT, SUN                  -> "Weekend";
  };

TEXT BLOCKS (Java 15):
  // Old: escaping hell
  String json = "{\"name\": \"Alice\", \"age\": 25}";

  // New: text block (triple quotes)
  String json = """
      {
          "name": "Alice",
          "age": 25
      }
      """;
  // Indentation is stripped relative to closing """

RECORDS (Java 16):
  // Immutable data classes — replaces verbose POJOs
  record Point(int x, int y) { }  // auto-generates: constructor, getters, equals, hashCode, toString

  Point p = new Point(3, 4);
  p.x();   // getter (not getX())
  p.y();
  // Compact canonical constructor for validation:
  record Range(int min, int max) {
    Range {
      if (min > max) throw new IllegalArgumentException();
    }
  }

IMMUTABLE COLLECTIONS (Java 9):
  List.of("a", "b", "c")      // unmodifiable
  Set.of(1, 2, 3)
  Map.of("k1", "v1", "k2", "v2")

COLLECTORS API:
  Collectors.toList()          // collect to list
  Collectors.toUnmodifiableList()  // Java 10
  Collectors.joining(", ")    // join strings
  Collectors.groupingBy()      // group by key
  Collectors.partitioningBy()  // split by predicate
  Collectors.counting()        // count per group
  Collectors.summingInt()      // sum per group

LOGGING WITH LOG4J:
  // pom.xml dependency: log4j-core
  Logger logger = LogManager.getLogger(MyClass.class);
  logger.info("Processing request for user {}", userId);
  logger.error("Database error", exception);
  logger.debug("SQL: {}", query);  // only logs in debug level

IOC (INVERSION OF CONTROL):
Traditionally, your code creates its own dependencies:
  UserService service = new UserService(new UserRepository(...));

With IOC, the framework creates and manages objects (called beans):
  @Service class UserService { ... }  // Spring creates and manages this

DEPENDENCY INJECTION (DI):
Spring injects dependencies into your objects automatically.

  @Service
  public class OrderService {
    private final UserRepository userRepo;
    private final EmailService emailService;

    // Constructor injection (PREFERRED)
    public OrderService(UserRepository userRepo, EmailService emailService) {
      this.userRepo     = userRepo;
      this.emailService = emailService;
    }
  }

SPRING BEANS:
  @Component   — generic Spring bean
  @Service     — business logic layer
  @Repository  — data access layer (adds exception translation)
  @Controller  — MVC controller
  @RestController — REST controller (@Controller + @ResponseBody)
  @Configuration — Java config class
  @Bean          — factory method in @Configuration class

SPRING MVC REQUEST FLOW:
  HTTP Request
    → DispatcherServlet (front controller)
    → HandlerMapping (finds @RequestMapping method)
    → Controller method executes
    → ViewResolver (for MVC) / MessageConverter (for REST)
    → HTTP Response

SPRING BOOT:
  Spring Boot = Spring + autoconfiguration + embedded server.
  No XML config. No WAR deployment. Just run the main class.
  @SpringBootApplication = @Configuration + @EnableAutoConfiguration + @ComponentScan

  @SpringBootApplication
  public class App {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
      SpringApplication.run(App.class, args);
    }
  }

REST PRINCIPLES:
  Stateless — server stores no client session
  Resource-based — URLs represent resources, not actions
  HTTP verbs — GET (read), POST (create), PUT (full update), PATCH (partial), DELETE
  Uniform interface — consistent URL structure

SPRING REST CONTROLLER:
  @RestController
  @RequestMapping("/api/users")
  public class UserController {

    @GetMapping
    public List<User> getAll() { return userService.findAll(); }

    @GetMapping("/{id}")
    public ResponseEntity<User> getById(@PathVariable Long id) {
      return userService.findById(id)
        .map(ResponseEntity::ok)
        .orElse(ResponseEntity.notFound().build());
    }

    @PostMapping
    public ResponseEntity<User> create(@RequestBody @Valid UserDto dto) {
      User created = userService.create(dto);
      URI location = URI.create("/api/users/" + created.getId());
      return ResponseEntity.created(location).body(created);
    }

    @PutMapping("/{id}")
    public User update(@PathVariable Long id, @RequestBody UserDto dto) {
      return userService.update(id, dto);
    }

    @DeleteMapping("/{id}")
    @ResponseStatus(HttpStatus.NO_CONTENT)
    public void delete(@PathVariable Long id) { userService.delete(id); }
  }

SWAGGER / OPENAPI:
  // Dependency: springdoc-openapi-starter-webmvc-ui
  // Access: http://localhost:8080/swagger-ui.html
  @Operation(summary = "Get user by ID")
  @ApiResponse(responseCode = "200", description = "User found")
  @ApiResponse(responseCode = "404", description = "User not found")
  @GetMapping("/{id}")
  public ResponseEntity<User> getById(@PathVariable Long id) { ... }

GLOBAL EXCEPTION HANDLING:
  @RestControllerAdvice
  public class GlobalExceptionHandler {
    @ExceptionHandler(ResourceNotFoundException.class)
    @ResponseStatus(HttpStatus.NOT_FOUND)
    public ErrorResponse handleNotFound(ResourceNotFoundException ex) {
      return new ErrorResponse(404, ex.getMessage());
    }
    @ExceptionHandler(MethodArgumentNotValidException.class)
    @ResponseStatus(HttpStatus.BAD_REQUEST)
    public ErrorResponse handleValidation(MethodArgumentNotValidException ex) {
      List<String> errors = ex.getBindingResult().getFieldErrors()
        .stream().map(FieldError::getDefaultMessage).toList();
      return new ErrorResponse(400, errors.toString());
    }
  }

ORM CONCEPTS:
  ORM = Object-Relational Mapping — maps Java objects to database tables.
  JPA = Java Persistence API — specification
  Hibernate = most popular JPA implementation

  @Entity
  @Table(name = "users")
  public class User {
    @Id @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)
    private Long id;

    @Column(nullable = false, length = 100)
    private String name;

    @ManyToOne
    @JoinColumn(name = "dept_id")
    private Department department;

    @OneToMany(mappedBy = "user", cascade = CascadeType.ALL)
    private List<Order> orders;
  }

SPRING DATA JPA REPOSITORY:
  public interface UserRepository extends JpaRepository<User, Long> {
    // Derived queries — Spring generates SQL automatically
    List<User> findByDepartmentName(String deptName);
    Optional<User> findByEmail(String email);
    List<User> findByAgeGreaterThanOrderBySalaryDesc(int age);

    // JPQL
    @Query("SELECT u FROM User u WHERE u.salary > :min AND u.dept = :dept")
    List<User> findHighEarners(@Param("min") double min, @Param("dept") String dept);

    // Native SQL
    @Query(value = "SELECT * FROM users WHERE YEAR(created_at) = :year", nativeQuery = true)
    List<User> findByYear(@Param("year") int year);
  }

LOCKING:
  Optimistic locking — no DB lock. Use @Version field.
  If two transactions update same row, second gets OptimisticLockException.
  @Version private Long version;  // Spring increments automatically

  Pessimistic locking — DB-level lock. Prevents concurrent reads/writes.
  @Lock(LockModeType.PESSIMISTIC_WRITE)
  @Query("SELECT u FROM User u WHERE u.id = :id")
  Optional<User> findByIdForUpdate(@Param("id") Long id);

TRANSACTIONS:
  @Transactional              // on service methods
  @Transactional(readOnly = true)  // optimization for read-only
  @Transactional(rollbackFor = Exception.class)

SPRING SECURITY:
  Handles authentication (who are you?) and authorization (what can you do?).
  Plugs into Spring MVC via a filter chain.

JWT (JSON Web Token):
  Structure: header.payload.signature (Base64URL encoded)
  Header: { alg: HS256, typ: JWT }
  Payload: { sub: userId, roles: [ADMIN], exp: timestamp }
  Signature: HMACSHA256(header + payload, secretKey)

  Stateless — server does NOT store sessions. Client sends token in header.
  Authorization: Bearer eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiJ9...

FLOW:
  1. POST /auth/login { username, password }
  2. Server validates credentials → generates JWT
  3. Client stores JWT (localStorage or httpOnly cookie)
  4. Client sends JWT in every request header
  5. Server validates JWT signature + expiry on each request

SPRING SECURITY CONFIG (Spring Boot 3):
  @Configuration
  @EnableWebSecurity
  public class SecurityConfig {
    @Bean
    public SecurityFilterChain filterChain(HttpSecurity http) throws Exception {
      return http
        .csrf(csrf -> csrf.disable())  // disabled for REST APIs
        .authorizeHttpRequests(auth -> auth
          .requestMatchers("/api/auth/**").permitAll()
          .requestMatchers("/api/admin/**").hasRole("ADMIN")
          .anyRequest().authenticated()
        )
        .sessionManagement(s -> s.sessionCreationPolicy(STATELESS))
        .addFilterBefore(jwtFilter, UsernamePasswordAuthenticationFilter.class)
        .build();
    }
  }

REACTIVE STACK:
  Spring WebFlux + Project Reactor (non-blocking)
  Mono<T>   — 0 or 1 item
  Flux<T>   — 0 to N items
  R2DBC     — reactive DB driver (non-blocking alternative to JDBC)
  Use when: high concurrency, streaming data, event-driven systems

SPRING CLOUD COMPONENTS:
  Service Discovery (Eureka): microservices register themselves; others discover by name
  API Gateway (Spring Cloud Gateway): single entry point, routes to services, handles auth
  Load Balancing (Spring Cloud LoadBalancer): distribute traffic across instances
  Config Server: centralized configuration for all services
  Circuit Breaker (Resilience4j): prevent cascade failures

SERVICE-TO-SERVICE COMMUNICATION:

  // Declarative with OpenFeign
  @FeignClient(name = "user-service")
  public interface UserClient {
    @GetMapping("/api/users/{id}")
    User getUserById(@PathVariable Long id);
  }

  // Inject and use like a regular interface
  @Service
  public class OrderService {
    private final UserClient userClient;
    public Order createOrder(Long userId) {
      User user = userClient.getUserById(userId);  // Feign handles HTTP
    }
  }

SPRING MESSAGING (JMS):
  JMS = Java Message Service — asynchronous messaging between services
  ActiveMQ or RabbitMQ as broker

  @JmsListener(destination = "order.queue")
  public void processOrder(Order order) {
    // process asynchronously
  }
  jmsTemplate.convertAndSend("order.queue", order);

UNIT TESTING:
  JUnit 5 + Mockito + Spring Boot Test
  @SpringBootTest — loads full context
  @WebMvcTest — loads only controller layer
  @DataJpaTest — loads only JPA layer

  @Test
  void testCreateUser() {
    when(userRepo.save(any())).thenReturn(mockUser);
    User result = userService.createUser(dto);
    verify(userRepo, times(1)).save(any());
    assertEquals("Alice", result.getName());
  }
